= Books

A single individual can only see the world through their own eyes and is thus inherently limited. Books, however, allow us to peek into other people's lives, at least temporarily, to extend our knowledge beyond artificially imposed boundaries. I believe we can learn a lot from fictional and real characters alike, and doing so in a very cost-efficient manner makes this an even more appealing prospect! Some of the most accomplished people in the world claim to read several hours a day (see [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eTFy8RnUkoU here] or [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uwJWaKP4Aus here]), so why would you not? Here are a few books I recently read which have had a long-lasting effect on me. Feel free to (dis)agree with my conclusions, and let me know what you think!
~~~
Disclaimer: None of the following books are indicative of my political persuasion or moral values - I enjoy these works solely for their literary craftmanship and creative spirit.
~~~

== Fiction
=== Ayn Rand: The Fountainhead
~~~
{}{raw}
<img src="Figures/Covers/The_Fountainhead.jpg" height="150px" hspace="10" padding-right:"20" align="left">
<p>Ayn Rand was an individual who firmly stood by her convictions of individuality, non-conformity, and personal virtue. Her beliefs are embedded in the story's main characters that are divided into two warring factions (individualists which live based on their virtues vs. conformists/"second handers" who live through others). While this is certainly a hugely motivating read for all those who "build" things against social norms, the novel's characters are often depicted in a crude and archetypical fashion, rendering them one-dimensional and simply unrelatable. Nevertheless, a key takeaway of this novel is to always stand your ground, defend your values, and chase your dreams, irrespective of what the environment expects you to be. In light of how quickly businesses (especially in technology) have been evolving and disrupted in recent decades, often defying society's expectations and conventional wisdom, this is an almost prophetic literary accomplishment.
</p>

<ul>
	<li><p><i>"Man cannot survive except through his mind. He comes on earth unarmed. His brain is his only weapon. Animals obtain food by force. Man had no claws, no fangs, no horns, no great strength of muscle. He must plant his food or hunt it. To plant, he needs a process of thought. To hunt, he needs weapons, and to make weapons - a process of thought. From this simplest necessity to the highest religious abstraction, from the wheel to the skyscraper, everything we are and we have comes from a single attribute of man -the function of his reasoning mind."</p></i></li>
	<li><p><i>"No creator was prompted by a desire to serve his brothers, for his brothers rejected the gift he offered and that gift destroyed the slothful routine of their lives. His truth was his only motive. His own truth, and his own work to achieve it in his own way. A symphony, a book, an engine, a philosophy, an airplane or a building—that was his goal and his life. Not those who heard, read, operated, believed, flew or inhabited the thing he had created. The creation, not its users. The creation, not the benefits others derived from it. The creation which gave form to his truth. He held his truth above all things and against all men."</p></i></li>
	<li><p><i>"That, precisely, is the deadliness of second-handers. They have no concern for facts, ideas, work. They're concerned only with people. They don't ask: 'Is this true?' They ask: 'Is this what others think is true?' Not to judge, but to repeat. Not to do, but to give the impression of doing. Not creation, but show. Not ability, but friendship. Not merit, but pull."</p></i></li>
</ul>
<br><br>
~~~

=== Ayn Rand: Atlas Shrugged
~~~
{}{raw}
<img src="Figures/Covers/Atlas_Shrugged.jpg" height="150px" hspace="10" padding-right:"20" align="left">
<p>This monumental, 1100-page literary behemoth emphasizes the importance of individual rights, rational selfishness, and the pursuit of happiness. It does so in a ruthless fashion by juxtaposing successful industrial magnates (who are portrayed as almost superhuman creatures) with government officials and lobbyists (all of which are characterized as weak and lazy &ldquo;looters&rdquo; and &ldquo;moochers&rdquo;). Throughout the course of the novel, Rand's philosophy of objectivism is presented to the reader in long monologues. Rand advocates for a laissez-faire free market economy in which any form of governmental control is considered evil and an encroachment on individual liberties. While the theory of objectivism offers valuable suggestions for a productive economy and the generation of wealth, it fails to account for people who lack the means to actively participate in a free-market economy or engage in intellectual, non-profit pursuits. Nevertheless, in these politically tumultuous times, Ayn Rand is more relevant than ever! Who is John Galt?
</p>

<ul>
	<li><p><i>"Humility - learn to value yourself, which means: to fight for your happiness - and when you learn that pride is the sum of all virtues, you will live like a man."</p></i></li>
	<li><p><i>"So you think that money is the root of all evil?&rdquo; said Francisco d’Anconia. "Have you ever asked what is the root of money? Money is a tool of exchange, which can't exist unless there are goods produced and men able to produce them. Money is the material shape of the principle that men who wish to deal with one another must deal by trade and give value for value. Money is not the tool of the moochers, who claim your product by tears, or of the looters, who take it from you by force. Money is made possible only by the men who produce. Is this what you consider evil?"</p></i></li>
	<li><p><i>"Any refusal to recognize reality, for any reason whatever, has disastrous consequences. There are no evil thoughts except one: the refusal to think."</p></i></li>
	<li><p><i>"The only proper purpose of a government is to protect man's rights, which means: to protect him from physical violence. The only proper functions of a government are: the police, to protect you from criminals; the army, to protect you from foreign invaders; and the courts, to protect your property and contracts from breach or fraud by others, to settle disputes by rational rules, according to objective law."</p></i></li>
</ul>
<br><br>
