== Business & Money
=== Benjamin Graham: The Intelligent Investor
~~~
{}{raw}
<img src="Figures/Covers/The_Intelligent_Investor.jpg" height="150px" hspace="10" padding-right:"20" align="left">
<p>The vast majority of actively managed funds underperform ordinary broad market index funds, yet to the layman the allure of "beating the market" encourages stock picking without doing proper research. More astonishingly, many people (including myself not too long ago) do not know how to invest at all. This book, however, teaches tried and true principles to all investors. Most importantly, it draws a clear line between "investing" and "speculating". This is a life-changing read that could very well make the difference between retiring in poverty or in <a href="https://www.topretirements.com/reviews/Florida/Boca_Raton.html">Boca Raton</a>.</p>
<ul>
	<li><p><i>"The intelligent investor is a realist who sells to optimists and buys from pessimists."</p></i></li>
	<li><p><i>"But investing isn't about beating others at their game. It's about controlling yourself at your own game."</p></i></li>
	<li><p><i>"People who invest make money for themselves; people who speculate make money for their brokers."</p></i></li>
	<li><p><i>"While enthusiasm may be necessary for great accomplishments elsewhere, on Wall Street it almost invariably leads to disaster."</p></i></li>
	<li><p><i>"But note this important fact: The true investor scarcely ever is forced to sell his shares, and at all other times he is free to disregard the current price quotation. He need pay attention to it and act upon it only to the extent that it suits his book, and no more. Thus the investor who permits himself to be stampeded or unduly worried by unjustified market declines in his holdings is perversely transforming his basic advantage into a basic disadvantage. That man would be better off if his stocks had no market quotation at all, for he would then be spared the mental anguish caused him by other persons' mistakes of judgment."</p></i></li>
	<li><p><i>"The sillier the market's behavior, the greater the opportunity for the business like investor."</p></i></li>
	<li><p><i>"The investor's chief problem – and even his worst enemy - is likely to be himself"</p></i></li>
</ul>
<br><br>
~~~

=== George Clason: The Richest Man in Babylon
~~~
{}{raw}
<img src="Figures/Covers/Richest_Man_Babylon.jpg" height="150px" hspace="10" padding-right:"20" align="left">
<p>This is a primer to personal finance that presents elementary concepts to build a financial safety net. The "10% rule" according to which one socks away 10% of each paycheck into income generating investments can secure financial freedom in the long run, given the effect of compounding over the years. While this books offers nothing more then the most basic of all principles, it is the narrative (parables set in ancient Babylon) that makes the book so compelling to read. The takeaway is that to become a wealthy person, one must first and foremost develop the right mindset, pay oneself first, and cut unnecessary expenses. (easier said than done ...)</p>
<ul>
	<li><p><i>"Would you call a fisherman lucky who for years so studied the habits of the fish that with each changing wind he could cast his nets about them? Opportunity is a haughty goddess who wastes no time with those who are unprepared."</li></p></i>
	<li><p><i>"How can you call yourself a free man when your weakness has brought you to this? If a man has in himself the soul of a slave will he not become one no matter what his birth, even as water seeks its level? If a man has within him the soul of a free man, will he not become respected and honoured in his own city in spite of his misfortune?"</li></p></i>
	<li><p><i>"To secure wealth quickly youth often borrows unwisely. Youth, never having had experience, cannot realize that hopeless debt is like a deep pit into which one may descend quickly and where one may struggle vainly for many days. It is a pit of sorrow and regrets where the brightness of the sun is overcast and night is made unhappy by restless sleeping."</li></p></i>
</ul>
<br><br>
~~~

=== Dale Carnegie: How to Win Friends and Influence People
~~~
{}{raw}
<img src="Figures/Covers/How_To_Win_Friends.jpg" height="150px" hspace="10" padding-right:"20" align="left">
<p>Sometimes it is worth remembering that "nothing that is worth knowing can be taught". Not so fast! Oscar Wilde specifically referred to education in classrooms when coining this phrase. When it comes to interactions with other people, Dale Carnegie presents basic principles for dealing more successfully with coworkers, friends, and strangers. This book teaches how to react to conflicts, influence people, and convince others by explaining fundamental principles of human psychology. Using praise and honest appreciation instead of criticism and calling to other people's mistakes indirectly are just a few pieces of advice to build and maintain better relationships with people. These principles all seem like common sense, however they are often difficult to stick to in practice, as we habitually fail to use huge parts of our physical and psychological resources. </p>
<ul>
	<li><p><i>"Ninety-nine times out of a hundred, people don't criticize themselves for anything, no matter how wrong it may be."</li></p></i>
	<li><p><i>"Any fool can criticize, condemn and complain - and most fools do. But it takes character and self-control to be understanding and forgiving."</li></p></i>
	<li><p><i>"Few people are logical. Most of us are prejudiced and biased. Most of us are blighted with preconceived notions, with jealousy, suspicion, fear, envy and pride."</li></p></i>
	<li><p><i>"If you wan't to gather honey, don't kick over the beehive."</li></p></i>
	<li><p><i>"Be hearty in your approbation and lavish in your praise."</li></p></i>
</ul>
<br><br>
