== Autobiographies
=== Chrissie Wellington: A Life Without Limits
~~~
{}{raw}
<img src="Figures/Covers/Life_Without_Limits.jpg" height="150px" hspace="10" padding-right:"20" align="left">
<p>Chrissie Wellington, a four-time Ironman World Champion from the UK, shares her incredible journey from her childhood to the world's biggest triathlon scene. Perhaps most surprisingly, she entered triathlon "by chance", and not before the age of 27. In this autobiography, we learn about Chrissie's early struggles with anorexia and quest for purpose in life, which initially led her to pursue a career in international development, far away from any athletic endeavors. It wasn't until she smashed the field at a local triathlon race that she turned professional. The rest is history. Chrissie's positive and energetic approach to life encouragees every hobby athlete to embrace adversity, overcome obstacles, and become a better person, not just in sports, but also in life. This is not a story of superhuman ability, but a brutally honest account of self-awareness and personal struggle, turning adversity into success. </p>
<ul>
	<li><p><i>"Remaining positive really is one of the most precious faculties for any athlete. That, and an ability to stay focused and disciplined. Develop a mind bank of positive images and thoughts—family, friends, previous successes, favorite places, a big plate of chips. You need to build it up as you would any collection, but soon you will have a range of thoughts to flick through when next your body and soul are screaming out for relief."</p></i></li>
	<li><p><i>"The best way of improving your capacity to endure boredom is to endure boredom. Spend time training on your own and challenge your mind to stay focused."</p></i></li>
	<li><p><i>"Hard work and an open mind—it’s the only way to realize the potential that is inside every one of us."</li></p></i>
</ul>
<br><br>
~~~

=== Ronnie O'Sullivan: Running
~~~
{}{raw}
<img src="Figures/Covers/Running.jpg" height="150px" hspace="10" padding-right:"20" align="left">
<p>Ronnie O'Sullivan is a professional snooker player from the UK and is widely considered a creative genius and the best to have ever played the sport. In this autobiography, we get to know the two sided Ronnie: On the one hand, the brilliant, charismatic, and creative genius at work, and on the other hand, the controversial, polarizing character that rebels against social norms and expectations. We learn that Ronnie is a complex character that often struggles to keep his emotions in check and fight self-doubt (he refers to the "chimp" in this head), initially relying on drugs to suppress his emotional hardship. Over time, the author describes how he manages to transform his drug addiction to a running addiction, thereby achieving better balance between his mind and his body, a phenomenon many hobby athletes can relate to. </p>
<ul>
	<li><p><i>"I used to rely on drugs and alcohol to keep me going, but now I've got the healthiest addiction going - running."
	</p></i></li>
	<li><p><i>"I'm not saying I'm right, but this is the life of most successful sportsmen. We need our routine; we need to be focused; we are selfish; we do have to put ourselves first."</p></i></li>
	<li><p><i>"Jogging is hard, but running is easy. Running is as easy as brushing your teeth. When you watch runners doing 10 kilometres in 27 minutes that isn't hard; it’s harder for the fella doing it in 54 minutes because he's using every muscle. When you're jogging it's a slog; you're using your shoulders, your hips, you're struggling to get your knees in front. When you're running, everything just flows. You get in such a rhythm, it's like a dance. Your body's not moving, your head's not moving, your shoulders aren't rolling. Your hips are coming through, your feet are off the ground a lot longer. You go past a set of lamp-posts and you’re thinking, I’m covering this ground really fast. You're just listening to your breath, your heart and your footsteps, and maybe a few birds twittering away. It's beautiful."</p></i></li>
</ul>
<br><br>
~~~

=== Andre Agassi: Open
~~~
{}{raw}
<img src="Figures/Covers/Open.jpg" height="150px" hspace="10" padding-right:"20" align="left">
<p>Andre Agassi, 8-time grand slam winner and widely considered one of the greatest tennis players ever, details his struggles and anxieties throughout his professional tennis career. To the layman it appears that life as a successful professional athlete is tantamount to fame, fortune, and constant happiness. Andre, however, takes the reader behind the scenes and describes how his brutal training regimen, loneliness, and abundant travel routine take a toll on his mental and physical health. In this autobiography, Andre describes how he was able to channel his rebellious nature as a kid into hard and consistent work, not minding picking occasional fights with his fellow tennis players. This is a great reflection on the career of a successful tennis player who gives us an honest glimpse into his emotional life.</p>
<ul>
	<li><p><i>"Life will throw everything but the kitchen sink in your path, and then it will throw the kitchen sink. It's your job to avoid the obstacles. If you let them stop you or distract you, you're not doing your job, and failing to do your job will cause regrets that paralyze you more than a bad back."
	</p></i></li>
	<li><p><i>"What you feel doesn’t matter in the end; it's what you do that makes you brave."</p></i></li>
	<li><p><i>"What makes something special is not just what you have to gain, but what you feel there is to lose."</p></i></li>
	<li><p><i>"Even if it's not your ideal life, you can always choose it. No matter what your life is, choosing it changes everything."</p></i></li>
</ul>
<br><br>
